Introduction to the Study

Old vs New: Stocks vs Crypto

The trend of investing in cryptocurrencies in the financial world has appeared quite recently and has only just begun to receive more general attention and gain wide popularity. It is only natural that one would wonder how cryptocurrency investors stack up to those in the much more established and centuries-old stock market. Cryptocurrencies are often regarded as higher-risk investments with high volatility compared to the conventional stocks but promising greater returns. This slant toward a high-risk, high-reward profile necessarily provokes deeper exploration into their performance.

Trying to understand some of these dynamics, I decided to look at the performance of cryptocurrency investments over the past few years. This analysis points to not only the impressive gains that some investors have realized but also the considerable risks and potential downsides associated with crypto investing. This can provide a better look at how the two compare in terms of the potential for profits, and, in turn, the potential for loss, compared to the performance of traditional stock markets. In this presintatuion I aimed to provide a balanced view, taking into account the unique opportunities that cryptocurrencies offer, at the same time as the substantial risks that they engender.

My final project attempts to answer some of the questions below:

  • What are the comparative performances of investments in cryptocurrencies versus traditional stock market investments such as the S&P 500 over various time frames?

  • What are the risk profiles associated with investing in cryptocurrencies compared to traditional equity investments?

Column

Variable Explanation

  • Date: The date on which the data was recorded (string format).
  • BTC: The price of Bitcoin on that date (floating-point number).
  • NYSE: The index value of the New York Stock Exchange on that date (floating-point number).
  • NASDAQ: The index value of the NASDAQ on that date (floating-point number).
  • BTC_Volume: The trading volume of Bitcoin on that date (integer).
  • NYSE_Volume: The trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange on that date (integer).
  • NASDAQ_Volume: The trading volume on the NASDAQ on that date (integer).
  • price: The price of Bitcoin on the given date (floating-point number).
  • total_volume: The total trading volume of Bitcoin on that date (floating-point number).
  • market_cap: The market capitalization of Bitcoin on that date (floating-point number).
  • coin_name: The name of the cryptocurrency, which is Bitcoin in this case (string).

Analysis

From the S&P 500 chart, one can see a tendency to grow the prices of the stock in the long run with only some corrections. In 2015 and now in 2020, it has had major downturns, which could be regarded as major economic events or market. The chart of Bitcoin presents a violent volatility in prices, thus giving an environment full of either very high potential risk or high potential reward, subject to multiple variables. It is in stark contrast to the steadier pattern of growth over the same period from the S&P 500, where rapid gains and then precipitous losses are more typical of the cryptocurrency markets.

Analysis

# A tibble: 2 × 4
  Investment AnnualizedReturns Volatility SharpeRatio
  <chr>                  <dbl>      <dbl>       <dbl>
1 S&P 500                6.50      1.16         0.110
2 Bitcoin                0.498     0.0373       0.682

The S&P 500 shows higher annualized returns at 6.50% with a volatility of 1.16, but a low Sharpe Ratio of 0.110 suggests less favorable risk-adjusted returns. Bitcoin, with an annualized return of 0.498% and a much lower volatility of 0.0373, has a higher Sharpe Ratio of 0.682, indicating better risk-adjusted returns despite its lower return.

Summary/Findings

An interesting insight about the performance of the investments analyzed from S&P 500 and Bitcoin is seen in the index’s returns and its risk profiles. The performance displayed in the market by the S&P 500 was largely strong, with an annualized return of 6.50%. However, these come with a volatility of 1.16, which signifies greater price variation and higher exposure to risk. However, this does come with a higher return as well, and the Sharpe Ratio from the S&P 500 indicates a return adjusted for risk of 0.110. The Sharpe Ratio is less, which tells us that the additional risks taken by the investors are not compensated well through the excess return of the S&P 500. Bitcoin, on the other hand, would have shown a completely different risk-return profile. With that said, it features a much smaller annualized return of 0.498%, while volatility was also lowered to 0.0373.Its lower volatility implies fewer and less serious price swings compared to the S&P 500. Most importantly, Bitcoin’s Sharpe Ratio of 0.682 was much higher than that of the S&P 500. This higher Sharpe Ratio indicates the possibility of better risk-adjusted returns from Bitcoin, meaning the returns over Bitcoin relative to its level of risk are more favorable than those of the S&P 500. This analysis, then, would conclude that if the S&P 500 offers somewhat larger absolute returns, Bitcoin offers a more efficient return on investment in comparison, again, when adjusted for risk. If an investor is looking for less volatility in his or her investment, or if an investor prefers the kind of risk management that limits higher potential gains, then Bitcoin is not the way to go. If a person is ready to assume higher risk in exchange for the chance of higher returns, they may prefer investing in the S&P 500. All these findings underline the importance of consideration not only of absolute returns but also of risk-adjusted returns while deciding on various investment opportunities. The choice to invest in traditional stock markets like the S&P 500 or to invest in a new asset class like Bitcoin would be theirs to make for an investor who would consider his risk appetite, investment horizon, and overall financial strategy.

References and Limitations

Limitations

Some potential limitations of my project include that: It relies on the CSV files of S&P 500 and Bitcoin data without data quality verification, which is very essential in accruing accurate results. The statistical methods assume that the financial data are normally distributed, something that may not necessarily be true in the real world due to deviations like skewness or fat tails. The fixed 30-day window for calculating the metrics might hide bigger trends. In addition, the project lacks the validation of the model by some very important out-of-sample data, and lastly, it does not touch on any externalities such as macroeconomic changes, which are very important influences of market prices. All these issues may be mitigated with better validation of data, other statistical approaches, model fit by various means, and even external variables.
